<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-323  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 323.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 17 1990 n287 p60(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Reality check: check-cashing ATMs exemplify how technology canincrease customer service. (automatic teller machines)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Epps, Richard W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The new check-cashing automatic teller machines (ATMs) show howtechnology can ease the handling of routine transactions, offerbetter service and free personnel to provide more responsive helpto customers.andP;  Check-cashing ATMs read the numbers printed inmagnetic ink in the lower-left corner of each check, identifyingand verifying the originating bank, account and check numberbefore dispensing cash.andP;  A test of the system by a CoreStatesFinancial Corp (Philadelphia, PA) affiliate showed that half ofall checks were cashed through use of the new ATMs.andP;  This enabledhuman tellers to spend more constructive time serving customerneeds and making them feel that they were more than an accountnumber.andP;  Other advantages included giving banks a competitive edgeand easing compliance with new federal regulations requiringcrediting of customer accounts with the value of local checkswithin two days.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Automated Teller MachinesCost Benefit AnalysisPerformance ImprovementCustomer RelationsUtilizationImpact Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>